content_chunks.content: This course covers the aspects, principles and types of non-refrigerant cooling systems, including passive and evaporative cooling, desiccant cooling, and other sustainable methods. Students will learn fundamental principles, technological applications, design strategies, and regulatory frameworks. Emphasis is placed on practical applications and integrating these systems with modern building designs, and colling capacity calculation and system simulation.

Technology for sustainable cooling system design and non-refrigerant cooling optimization - this course delivers comprehensive expertise in evaporative cooling technology and passive cooling methods using advanced desiccant cooling systems and radiant cooling applications. Students will master ground cooling systems, phase change materials (PCMs) implementation, and night ventilation strategies for optimal heat recovery ventilation integration. The curriculum focuses on practical cooling system regulations compliance, cooling performance metrics evaluation, and cooling system optimization techniques for human-centric cooling design applications. Participants will gain hands-on experience with building cooling integration approaches, cooling system troubleshooting methodologies, and cooling system simulation tools. The program emphasizes environmental impact assessment, refrigerant-based cooling cycles analysis, and natural refrigerants understanding for comprehensive sustainable cooling technologies development.

content_chunks.title: Fundamentals of cooling and heat transfer
Legislation and regulatory standards for cooling systems
Optimization and energy efficiency in cooling systems
Integrating cooling systems with building design
Software tools for cooling system assessment
Policy and regulatory impacts on cooling systems
Environmental impact and life cycle assessment (LCA)
